1 Pre-Processing

The following steps prepare the dataset for the modeling part. The actual feature analysis was done in another kernel.

2 Modeling

2.1 Preparation

The dataset is split back into training and test.

train <- full[label == "train", !c("Id", "label")]
rownames(train) <- full[label == "train", Id]
test <- full[label == "test", !c("Id", "label", "SalePrice")]
rownames(test) <- full[label == "test", Id]

Sparse matrix with factors coded as 0 and 1.

X <- sparse.model.matrix(~ -1 + ., data = train[, !"SalePrice"])
Y <- train$SalePrice

2.2 Training

Split data for model selection. Big training set good for training, but less accurate validation result. Chose 25% 75% split

set.seed(42)
split <- sample(1:nrow(X), round(nrow(X) / 4))
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X[-split, ], label = Y[-split])
dval <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X[split, ], label = Y[split])

Objective function is linear regression (which is suared loss I think). Eta usually small 0.01, nround high enough. MARS model suggested rather additive model with no interaction terms. Therefore, look at low max.depth 2 or 4. Some subsampling (without replacement) is good against overfitting and can usually be set to araound 50%.

fit <- xgb.train(booster = "gbtree", data = dtrain,  eta = .01, max.depth = 4, 
                 subsample = .5, nround = 10000, objective = "reg:linear",
                 watchlist = list(train = dtrain, test = dval))

By default linear regression already returns RMSE. This is what it usually looks like. 10000 iterations seem sufficient to reach minimum test error with eta 0.01.

dt <- melt(fit$evaluation_log, "iter", c("train_rmse", "test_rmse"))
ggplot(dt) + 
  geom_path(aes(x = iter, y = value, color = variable)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, .2)) +
  theme_bw()

Below number of leafs and weighted number of observations (cover) which end up at certain depth. With this settings trees are mostly built to full length. As far as I know, in the regression setting the number of observations ending up in a single leaf can be directly translated to child weight. So, for a maximum of max.depth = 4 it would not make sense to search min_child_weight above around 150.

xgb.plot.deepness(model = fit)

2.3 Squared Loss

I came up with following grid. I chose to try out some values for L1 regularization. Also I try out colsample_bytree. For these two values I have no clue how they should be set.

pars.grid <- expand.grid(
  eta = c(0.01, 0.001),
  gamma = c(0, 0.01),
  max_depth = c(2, 4),
  min_child_weight = c(1, 50, 100),
  alpha = c(0, 0.5),
  colsample_bytree = c(1, 0.8)
)

Iterations to 10000 looked fine in plots. Subsampling to 50%. This reduces learning rate further but 10000 iterations should still be fine. Included early stopping if after more than 1000 rounds there was no improvement.

train.grid <- function(train, val, pars, n = 10000, subs = .5,
                       bstr = "gbtree", objFun = "reg:linear") {
  N <- nrow(pars)
  out <- data.frame(iter = integer(N), rmse = numeric(N))
  for (i in seq_len(N)) {
    fit <- xgb.train(booster = bstr, data = train, eta = pars$eta[i], 
                     gamma = pars$gamma[i], max.depth = pars$max_depth[i], 
                     min_child_weight = pars$min_child_weight[i], 
                     subsample = subs, alpha = pars$alpha[i], 
                     colsample_bytree = pars$colsample_bytree[i], 
                     nround = n, watchlist = list(train = dtrain, test = dval), 
                     objective = objFun, early_stopping_rounds = 1000)  
    dt <- fit$evaluation_log
    idx <- which.min(dt$test_rmse)
    out$iter[i] <- idx
    out$rmse[i] <- dt$test_rmse[idx]  
  }
  return(out)
}

On the plot above the effects of different parameters are nicely visible. Tree depth 2 is overall better than 4, increasing minimum child weight increased RMSE, \(\eta\) of 0.01 is better than 0.001 (maybe that would need more iterations), \(L_1\) regularization increased error overall, a \(\gamma\) of 0.01 did slightly better than 0, in some cases the 80% column sampling by tree decreased RMSE slightly. The differences in RMSE for minimum child weight seem most drastic with \(\delta\)RMSE of 0.01, followed by \(\eta\) with \(\delta\)RMSE of around 0.005. The best parameter combination is:

pars1 <- list(
  iter = 7366,
  eta = 0.01,
  gamma = 0.01,
  max_depth = 2,
  min_child_weight = 1,
  alpha = 0,
  colsample_bytree = 0.8
)

2.4 Huberized Loss

Huber objective function against outliers.

obj <- logregobj <- function(preds, dtrain) {
  labels <- getinfo(dtrain, "label")
  grad <- ifelse(abs(preds - labels < 1.5),
                 preds - labels,
                 1.5 * sign(preds - labels))
  hess <- ifelse(abs(preds - labels < 1.5), 1, 0)
  return(list(grad = grad, hess = hess))
}

Train same grid with this objective function.

res <- train.grid(dtrain, dval, pars.grid, objFun = obj)
df <- cbind(res, pars.grid)
df[which.min(df$rmse), ]
##    iter     rmse  eta gamma max_depth min_child_weight alpha
## 51 7366 0.099746 0.01  0.01         2                1     0
##    colsample_bytree
## 51              0.8
ggplot(df, aes(x = min_child_weight, y = rmse)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(eta), shape = as.factor(alpha))) +
  facet_grid(max_depth ~ gamma + colsample_bytree) +
  theme_bw()
